1.1. Load and Preprocess Data¶

Product quantities were not considered.

Limitations¶

Due to a problem in the database quantity (QTY) column, the SessionID that corresponds to an equivalent ID in Buys, was thus considered as a purchase. Altough this skews the expected results, the fact some buys had quantities of 0 and other problems, this was a temporarly, yet accurate metric of products and their given clicks and purchases

We also add to limit the database being loaded, namely store-clicks.dat, which we only took into account the top 50% of it. This will skew the results but we believe that not only was it acceptable and necessary, considering how big the database is, we can still find useful info.

#ignore prices/quantities of 0
#buys_upd = buys_upd[buys_upd.Price>0]

product_name_buys=[]
for cat in buys_upd.Category:
  product_name_buys.append(cat.split('.')[-1].replace('_',' ').title())
product_name_clicks=[]
for cat in clicks_upd.Category:
  product_name_clicks.append(cat.split('.')[-1].replace('_',' ').title())
#product_name[:5]

buys_upd['ProductName']= product_name_buys
buys_upd = buys_upd.drop('Category', axis=1)
clicks_upd['ProductName']=product_name_clicks
clicks_upd=clicks_upd.drop('Category', axis=1)

dates_buys =[]
season_buys =[]
dates_clicks =[]
season_clicks =[]

for i in buys_upd["TimeStamp"]:
  dates_buys.append(i[:10])
  if i[5:7] == "04" or i[5:7] == "05":
     season_buys.append("Spring")
  elif i[5:7] == "06" or i[5:7] == "07":
    season_buys.append("Summer")
  else:
    season_buys.append("Other")

for i in clicks_upd["TimeStamp"]:
  dates_clicks.append(i[:10])
  if i[5:7] == "04" or i[5:7] == "05":
     season_clicks.append("Spring")
  elif i[5:7] == "06" or i[5:7] == "07":
    season_clicks.append("Summer")
  else:
    season_clicks.append("Other")

weekday_buys=[]
buys_upd["TimeStamp"] = pd.to_datetime(buys_upd["TimeStamp"])
buys_upd["Weekday_Num"]=buys_upd["TimeStamp"].dt.dayofweek 
for i in buys_upd["Weekday_Num"]:
  if i < 5: 
    weekday_buys.append("Weekday")
  else:
    weekday_buys.append("Weekend")

weekday_clicks=[]
clicks_upd["TimeStamp"] = pd.to_datetime(clicks_upd["TimeStamp"])
clicks_upd["Weekday_Num"]=clicks_upd["TimeStamp"].dt.dayofweek 
for i in clicks_upd["Weekday_Num"]:
  if i < 5: 
    weekday_clicks.append("Weekday")
  else :
    weekday_clicks.append("Weekend")
  
buys_upd = buys_upd.drop(columns=['TimeStamp'])
buys_upd.insert(1, "TimeStamp", dates_buys)
buys_upd["Season"] = season_buys
buys_upd["Weekday"] = weekday_buys
buys_upd.sort_values(by='TimeStamp')

clicks_upd = clicks_upd.drop(columns=['TimeStamp'])
clicks_upd.insert(1, "TimeStamp", dates_clicks)
clicks_upd["Season"] = season_clicks
clicks_upd["Weekday"] = weekday_clicks
buys_upd=buys_upd.sort_values(by='SessionID').reset_index(drop=True)

1.2. Compute Frequent Itemsets¶

Due to restraints in processing power, some of the computing was done outside Google Colab, due to this the respective prints and subsequent analysis will be provided and the used code will be posted.

For sake of performance, it was decided to only use fpgrowth as it was the fastest option, as well as using less memory than apriori. From our tests, the result difference was negligenciable

In [ ]:
#Setting up: Which products are bought together?
all_sessions_buy={}
for i in range(len(buys_upd)):
  all_sessions_buy[buys_upd.SessionID[i]]=[]
for i in range(len(buys_upd)):
  if buys_upd.ProductName[i] not in all_sessions_buy.get(buys_upd.SessionID[i]):
    all_sessions_buy[buys_upd.SessionID[i]].append(buys_upd.ProductName[i])

transactions_buy=list(all_sessions_buy.values())

#Compute binary databases

binary_database_click = pd.DataFrame(trans_array_click, columns = tr_enc.columns_)

Frequent most bought itemsets considering a minimum support of 1%.¶

As already stated, we decided to use fp-Growth as it's performance for large databases is better than apriori. This is supported by academic research as one of the most commonly used algorithms for finding frequent itemsets while being less performance intensive.

We'd like to refer to this paper for research comparisons and choice reasoning: https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Comparison-of-Apriori-Eclat-and-FP-Growth-algorithm-on-artificial-dataset-when-the_fig2_272864559

In [ ]:
#FP-Growth é melhori que apriori
#buys
frequent_itemsets_fpg_buy = fpgrowth(binary_database_buy, min_support=0.01, use_colnames=True)
frequent_itemsets_fpg_buy['length'] = frequent_itemsets_fpg_buy['itemsets'].apply(lambda x: len(x))
frequent_itemsets_fpg_buy.sort_values(by='support', ascending=False).reset_index()

Association Rules from Frequent Itemsets¶

  • Generate association rules with a choosed value (C) for minimum confidence.
  • Generate association rules with a choosed value (L) for minimum lift.
  • Generate association rules with both confidence >= C% and lift >= L.
  • Change C and L when it makes sense and discuss the results.
In [ ]:
# Generate association rules with confidence >= 90%
rules_buy = association_rules(frequent_itemsets_fpg_buy, metric = "confidence", min_threshold=0.10)
rules_buy_lift = association_rules(frequent_itemsets_fpg_buy, metric="lift", min_threshold=1.2)
rules_buy_lift[(rules_buy_lift['lift'] >= 2)].sort_values(by='lift', ascending=False).reset_index()
rules_buy

At first a minimum Lift threshold of 1.2 was used, however this proved to be a few too many, which will be explored below.

However we can denote a few items that are closely bought together, namely Fans and Memory chips, which overall display the higher confidence, lift and conviction. Altough the support isn't the highest, that is, the given pair doesn't appear that often in the baskets, when they do, they have a strong correlation.

Given it's high confidence threshold, the implication that it's usually bought together is given as quite truthful. The same is true for the overall lifts of the given output itemsets. Given a Lift higher than 1, this lets us know the degree to which those two occurrences are dependent on one another.

This said both Fans and Memory chips strongly correlate with each other, the same is true for the following items, Memort Chips and Tennis, and Steam Cleaners and Lawn Mowers.

Products Sales - Ordered by Lift and Higher Confidence

These top itemsets are the ones we're iterested at, as they are the most commonly bought together, which a store manager or marketing department could take advantage of if discounts or similar promotions are considered in the future.

A few things to take in mind is that many outdoor related items are bought, as given the high range of categories provided, this category should be given the most attention of marketing team.

Maximal Patterns: Compute Maximal Frequent Itemsets¶

Maximal Frequent Itemsets are frequent itemsets without a frequent superset. Thus, by generating only maximal frequent itemsets we can reduce the number of itemsets calculated and also the time needed for the generation of said itemsets as each maximal itemset implies the presence of same length itemsets. As most previous calculation of Frequent Itemsets have been very performance intensive, Maximal Frequent Itemsets have proven to be quite fast and reliable

Maximal bought itemsets - Ordered by Support

Rules:

  • Support > 1%
In [ ]:
rules_buy_fmax = fpmax(binary_database_buy, min_support=0.01, use_colnames=True)
rules_buy_fmax['length'] = rules_buy_fmax['itemsets'].apply(lambda x: len(x))
rules_buy_fmax.sort_values(by='support', ascending=False).reset_index()

In the above image we can see all the Maximal Frequent Itemsets above 1% threshold of the store-buys.dat database however the ones with most support are single item which for the purpose of this report we'll discard in favor of >= 2, which we'll discuss next. However we should point the novelty appearance of some products, like Monitors, with 5.7% Support, Tonometers and Vacuums, with 5.4 and 4.7 percent, respectively.

Maximal bought itemsets - Ordered by Support

  • Length >= 2

Conclusions¶

As previously discussed, the apriori algorithm was discarded as a possibility due to it's high cost of performance. We chose FP-Growth as the base to analyze frequent itemsets of both clicks and purchases.

The most bougth and searched products are outdoor related, namely Tennis products, Lawn Mowers and Grills. There's also a high number of Memory Chips being bought as well as Blenders.

A few interesting points is that the most clicked items and respective itemsets are not the same as the ones being bought, with Fans, Monitors and Tosters usually appearing in the top 5 of all our findings, unlike the top purchased items that as said, are usually outdoor related.

As seen in the Heat Map of sales of most sold products, the Weekend is usually the busiest day, as was to be expected. Curiously, Mondays are busier than Saturdays. We believe the Heat Map to be an interesting overall analysis of the database, as not only does it show the most single sold item, it also shows when, which in the future could be used for more targeted marketing and stock management

It's also curious how small the Support threshold had to be in all of our computations, as any value higher than 2 was given back as empty. However considering how large the database is, both in the number of products sold and the sale number, we believe this is because of sales entropy and noise.

2. Week vs Weekend Purchases¶

2.2. Compute Frequent Itemsets¶

We varied the support metric in the FPGrowth process to see the difference in outputs. Using support = 5% leads to no relevant itemsets with length greater than 1 so to explore which products are clicked/bought together we must lower the minimal support.

Using support = 0.5% we obtained 2-itemsets for both store-buys and store-clicks, in the weekend and in workdays , we also obtained 3-itemsets for the weekend data but their support was so low that no credible conclusion could be obtained.

We decided to continue our analysis with minimal support = 1% because that way we could analyze 2-itemsets while also cutting down irrelevant information brought by a lower minimal support.

We also tried a minimal support < 0.5% which crashed the run due to the impossibility of allocation of memory necessary to subdue the store-clicks data set to FPGrowth.

We used the mlxtends association_rules function to obtain strong association rules between frequent itemsets for each dataset.

Since lift takes into account the overall populary of the antecedent itemsets is is a better metric to determine association rules’ streght, so after some consideration we considered strong the association rules with lift >=1.5 and obviously support >= 1%. We selected only associations with lift far from 1.

Clicks vs Sales analysis : Workdays¶

The most clicked on 1-itemsets during working days are (Tennis) (with a support of 17%), (Memory), (Blender), (Toster) and (Meat Grinder), by that order, containing an overall support of 54% while also satisfying the 1% minimal support mark.

The most clicked on 2-itemsets where mostly combinations of these most popular 1-itemsets, as expected. Some examples by order of relevance are (Tennis, Memory), (Blender, Memory), (Tennis, Toster), (Memory, Fan) and (Tennis, Notebook) and between them they have 9% of support.

The two 1-itemsets most clicked on during the week are also the most sold during the week: (Tennis), (Memory) and (Blender) with a total support of 25%. Others like (Lawn Mower), (Gaming) and (Monitor) are not the most clicked on during the week but are some of the most sold itemsets during the week.

With a minimum support of 1% the Apriori algorithm could only generate two frequent tuples of items for sales during the week which are (Lawn Mower, Tennis), (Tennis, Memory) and they have a combined support of 2,5%.

Once more the most frequent items (clicked or sold) individually compose the most frequent groups of items, as expected.

In general, the most popular items during the week seem to be also heavily sold during the week.

Clicks vs Sales analysis : Weekends¶

On the weekends the most popular 1-itemsets that are clicked are, in order, (Tennis), (Memory) and (Toster) with close to 50% overall support, and then (Blender), (Notebook) and (Monitor) with an adicional 23% of support.

The most clicked on 1-itemsets seem to be almost the same during the week and weekend , with exception to the (Blender) which is most popular during the week.

With 1% minimal support we could also compute popular 2-itemsets. The most popular ones are the same as in the weekdays except for (Tennis, Notebook) which is most popular during the week. This is not a surprise since both weekday and weekend datasets share a lot of most popular 1-itemsets.

We could also compute popular 3-itemsets during the weekend with a total of 1,6% support : (Fan, Tennis, Memory), (Blender, Tennis, Memory) . Which once again are combinations of the most popular 1-itemsets.

The top three sold 1-itemsets on the weekend are also the most clicked on during the weekend. Then the most sold items in the weekend after those are (Steam Cleaner) and (Lawn Mower) which are not particulary clicked on during the weekend nor on the weekdays.

The most sold 2-itemsets during the weekend are (Tennis, Lawn Mower) and (Tennis, Memory).

Workdays vs Weekends analysis¶

(Tennis) and (Memory) are the most clicked on and bought itemsets during the week and weekend.

(Tosters) are heavily clicked on and bought during the weekend while (Blenders) are more clicked on and bought during the weekdays.

2.3. Generate Association Rules from Frequent Itemsets¶

We used the mlxtends association_rules function to obtain strong association rules between frequent itemsets for each dataset.

Since lift takes into account the overall popularity of the antecedent itemsets is is a better metric to determine association rules’ strength, so after some consideration we considered as strong the association rules with lift >=1.5 and obviously support >= 1%.

We selected only associations with lift far from 1 to only look at cases where the antecedent itemsets influence the sale/popularity of the consequent itemsets.

In [ ]:
#Association Rules:
rules_click_wd = association_rules(frequent_itemsets_clicks_wd, metric="confidence", min_threshold=0.01)# to get maximum associations
filtered_rules_click_wd = rules_click_wd[(rules_click_wd['lift'] >= 1.5)].sort_values(by='lift',ascending=False)
filtered_rules_click_wd= filtered_rules_click_wd[['antecedents','consequents','support','confidence','lift']]

rules_click_we = association_rules(frequent_itemsets_clicks_we, metric="confidence", min_threshold=0.01)# to get maximum associations

filtered_rules_click_we= filtered_rules_click_we[['antecedents','consequents','support','confidence','lift']]

These where the association rules with biggest lift in all datasets considered, which means that the associations between frequently bought itemsets during the weekend are the strongest.

Which makes sense, people usually buy multiple products in the weekend which is when there is more time to browse and shop, so in the weekend it's easier for a sale of a product to influence the sale of another.

Buying a (Drill) strongly and positively influences the sale of a (Steam Cleaner), and vice-versa. We find the same positive influence between (Fan) and (Memory), (Vacuum) and (Grill) , and (Grill) and (Lawn Mower).

summer_dict={}

          newline='') as csvfile:

                                  fieldnames=['SessionID','TimeStamp',
                                              'ItemID','Price','Qty'])
          for row in reader:
            if row['TimeStamp']>='2014-06-01' and row['TimeStamp']<'2014-08-01':
              if row['SessionID'] not in summer_dict:

3.3. Generate Association Rules from Frequent Itemsets¶

  • Generate association rules with a choosed value (C) for minimum confidence.
  • Generate association rules with a choosed value (L) for minimum lift.
  • Generate association rules with both confidence >= C% and lift >= L.
  • Change C and L when it makes sense and discuss the results.

The final values for confidence and lift were determined by looking at the results of association rules using lower metric values. We tried to find the largest difference between metric values and used that as the boundary between relevant and non-relevant rules.

4. Conclusions¶

Most Bought & Clicked Itemsets¶

One of the most consistent pattern founds are that the mined itemsets tend to be outdoor related. Even when using different algorithms and rules, the premisse holds true throughout, which while expected is assuring of the recurrency of the statement.

To further expand on the analysis, more variables could be verified, such as if the products popularity and its clicks vary during seasons and by how much. Hopefuly this will be done in a future assignment.

The analysis would also have been different if all clicks within the database had been considered and not only 50%. If given more time, optimizations and further improvements were to be made in a future analysis, the results would have been more accurate and descriptive. However considering the still large amount of data used, we still consider our presented analysis as usable.

Week vs Weekend¶

We found that the items normally clicked on during the week are mostly sold during the week , and the ones clicked on during the weekend tend to sell better during the weekend.

The top two most clicked items are also the most sold items, regardless if it's a workday or the weekend.

We found that the strongest association rules can be found between itemsets bought on a weekend. While the weakest are found between itemsets bought on a workday.

The association rules found between clicked itemsets were mostly of the same strength and roughly the same nature (same popular rules), and it didn't seem to matter if we were analysing workday's data or weekend's.

Spring vs Summer¶

When it comes to Spring vs Summer, there is an obvious tendency towards garden and garden-related items during the Summer months (June and July), both in products bought and products clicked. The results for frequent items in the Spring (April and May) are close to the overall most bought and clicked on products during the year.

The associations found for the Summer months also reflect the most bought items, although the strongest (and less obvious) association found was between PC_Memory and Toasters.

The associations for clicks during the Summer months are mostly for garden-related products, with the only exception being Monitors and Tennis.

For the Spring months there are no season-related associations, unlike in the Summer. However, the associations found are very strong, both for sales and for clicks, and can be considered more interesting (PC_Memory-Fans and Lawn_Mower-Tennis) than the ones found for the Summer.

We found that the associations found heavily depend on what the threshold for relevant association is. We had some difficulty coming up with adequate limits that are not too restrictive but show only associations that might actually be relevant. This was one of the more important decisions of the project as it highly influences the final results.
